== Origins and History ==
According to tradition, the shrine was established in {{ill|Tengyō|ja|天慶|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 1 ({{ill|938|ja}}) by {{ill|Taira no Masakado|ja|Taira no Masakado|1=Taira no Masakado|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, who enshrined the deity of the {{ill|Kitano Tenmangū|ja|北野天満宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in Kyoto at this location. A hanging scroll depicting {{ill|Sugawara no Michizane|ja|Sugawara no Michizane|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, which includes a record of this origin, remains preserved. It is also noted that {{ill|Nichiren|ja|Nichiren|qq=draft|qq=draft}} performed a dedication ceremony for the shrine. Later, Honkōji Temple became the shrine’s {{ill|bettō|ja|別当|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (caretaker temple), and it has remained under the temple’s management since the {{ill|Meiji era|ja|明治時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
== Honkōji Temple Historical Records ==
* In {{ill|An'ei|ja|安永|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 7 ({{ill|1778|ja}}), the 19th head priest of Honkōji, Kangu-in {{ill|Nichishō (Honkōji)|ja|日正|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Nichishō), restored the deity {{ill|Tenman Daijizai Tenjin|ja|天満大自在天神|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. * From February to March of {{ill|Tenmei|ja|天明|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 5 ({{ill|1785|ja}}), Nichishō (Nichishō) replaced the roof of the Tenman Tenjin-gū.
== Related Articles ==
* {{ill|Ōno Castle (Shimōsa Province)|ja|大野城 (下総国)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} * {{ill|Ōno Tenmangū|ja|大野天満宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
